System Design
|
├── 1. Requirements
│   ├── Functional Requirements
│   │   → What the system should do (features, user actions, workflows).
│   │
│   └── Non-Functional Requirements (SCALD)
│       ├── Scaling → Ability to handle growing users/traffic
│       ├── Consistency → Data correctness across nodes/same data visible to all at any time
│       ├── Availability → System uptime and accessibility
│       ├── Latency → Response time of requests should be low
│       └── Durability → Data persistence even after failures
│
├── 2. Architecture
│   ├── Monolithic
│   │   → Single application where all components are tightly coupled.
│   │       When to use: Small apps / MVPs, Simple business logic
│   │
│   ├── Microservices
│   │   → System split into small independent services communicating via APIs.
|   |       When to use: Large, complex systems, Independent scaling needed
│   │
│   ├── Event-Driven
│   │   → Components communicate through events/messages (publish-subscribe).
│   │       When to use:Real-time processing (notifications, streams), asynchronous
│   ├── Serverless
│   │   → Cloud provider manages infrastructure; code runs on demand.
|   |       When to use: Variable/low traffic
│   │
│   ├── Stateful
│   │   → Services store session/state information locally.
|   |      When to use: Sessions needed (e.g., carts, gaming)
│   │
│   └── Stateless
│       → Each request is independent; easier to scale horizontally.
|   |      When to use: Cloud-native apps
│
├── 3. Communication & Networking
│   │
│   ├── Networking Fundamentals
│   │   ├── DNS → Converts domain names to IP addresses.
│   │   ├── TCP / UDP → Transport protocols for reliable vs fast communication.
│   │   ├── IP Addressing → Identifies devices in a network.
│   │   └── VPC / Subnets → Isolated cloud networks and internal segmentation.
│   │
│   ├── Communication Patterns
│   │   ├── Synchronous
│   │   │   → Immediate response required (HTTP, REST, SOAP, GraphQL, gRPC).
|   |         REST-> HTTP-based, resource-oriented, Uses GET, POST, PUT, DELETE
|   |                  When to Use-> Simple CRUD APIs, Public-facing services
|   |
|   |              GraphQL-> Single endpoint, Client requests exact fields
|   |             When to Use -> Complex UI data needs, Avoid over/under-fetching
|   |
|   |              SOAP-> XML-based protocol
|   |                  When to Use-> Banking systems, Enterprise & legacy apps
|   |
|   |             gRPC-> Uses HTTP/2, Binary protocol (Protobuf)
|   |                 When to Use-> Microservices, Internal service communication, Low-latency systems
|   |
|   |              WebSocket-> Persistent, full-duplex connection, Real-time data flow
|   |                  When to Use-> Chat apps, Live dashboards
│   │   │
│   │   └── Asynchronous
│   │       → Message-based communication using queues/streams.
│   │       (RabbitMQ, Kafka)
|   |      -> RabbitMQ: Uses queues, Producers → send messages → queue → consumers receive & delete
|   |         RabbitMQ is great for: Task queues (background jobs), Microservices communication (request/response), Complex routing logic
|   |      -> Kafka: Uses topics (logs), Messages are appended and stored for a set time, Consumers read at their own pace (can replay messages)
|   |         Kafka is ideal for: Event streaming (analytics, logs), Real-time data pipelines, Event sourcing systems
│   │
│   ├── Infrastructure
│   │   ├── API Gateway →The single entry point for all client requests in a system (especially microservices). 
|   |        (authentication & authorization, Rate limiting, logging, caching, routes requests to the right service).
|   |        Ex: AWS API Gateway, NGINX
│   │   ├── Forward Proxy → A forward proxy sits between the client and the internet.
|   |       Hides client identity (IP masking), Bypasses restrictions, Caches responses
│   │   └── Reverse Proxy → A reverse proxy sits in front of servers and represents them to clients.
|   |       Load balancing, SSL termination: Ex: NGINX, HAProxy
│   │
│   └── Traffic Control
│       └── Rate Limiting
│           → Restrict number of requests from users/services to prevent abuse.
│
├── 4. Data Management
│   ├── Databases
│   │   ├── SQL → Structured relational databases with strong consistency.(ACID)
│   │            Atomicity → All or nothing(all transactions should pass or fail)
│   │            Consistency → Valid state always
│   │            Isolation → No interference(like ticket booking)
│   │            Durability → Data is permanent
│   │   └── NoSQL → Flexible schema, optimized for scalability.
│   │            BASE
│   │            Basically Available → System always responds
│   │            Soft State → Data may change over time
│   │            Eventual Consistency → Data becomes consistent later
│   │
│   ├── Data Modeling
│   │   ├── Normalization → Reduce redundancy and improve integrity.
│   │   └── Denormalization → Duplicate data to improve query performance.
│   │
│   └── Data Distribution
│       ├── Replication → Copy data across nodes for availability.
│       ├── Sharding → Split data across servers for scalability.
│       └── CAP Theorem → Trade-off between Consistency, Availability, Partition tolerance.
│
├── 5. Storage
│   ├── Block Storage: Raw disk blocks (like a hard drive)
│   │   When to use: OS / Boot disks, Databases, High-performance apps,( Virtual machines → Persistent disks)
│   │
│   ├── Object Storage: → Stores data as objects with metadata (flat structure)
│   │   Whento use: Images, videos, backups, Logs, large scale data.
|   |   
│   ├── File Storage: Files in folders (shared filesystem)
│   │   When to use: Shared drives (team files), Content management systems
│   │
│   └── Backup & Disaster Recovery
│       → Data backup strategies to recover from failures.
│
├── 6. Fault Tolerance
│   ├── Redundancy
│   │   → Duplicate components to avoid single point of failure.
│   │
│   ├── Failover
│   │   → Automatic switch to standby system if primary fails.
│   │
│   └── Disaster Recovery
│       → Restore systems after major outages or data loss.
│
├── 7. Scaling
│   ├── Horizontal Scaling
│   │   → Add more servers to distribute load.
│   │
│   ├── Vertical Scaling
│   │   → Increase CPU/RAM of existing server.
│   │
│   └── Auto Scaling
│       → Automatically scale resources based on traffic.
│
├── 8. Security
│   ├── Cybersecurity Principles
│   │   ├── CIA Triad → Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability.
│   │   ├── Threat Modeling → Identify and mitigate potential attacks.
│   │   └── Zero Trust → Never trust any user/device without verification.
│   │
│   ├── Network Security
│   │   ├── Firewall → Filters network traffic based on security rules.
│   │   ├── WAF → Protects web apps from attacks (SQL injection, XSS).
│   │   └── Security Groups → Cloud firewall rules controlling traffic.
│   │
│   ├── Authentication (AuthN)
│   │   → Verifying user identity (passwords, tokens, biometrics).
│   │
│   ├── Authorization (AuthZ)
│   │   → Controlling what authenticated users are allowed to access.
│   │
│   └── Encryption
│       ├── SSL / TLS → Secure communication between client and server.
│       └── Data Encryption → Protect stored data from unauthorized access.
│
├── 9. Monitoring
│   ├── Logging
│   │   → Record system events and errors for debugging.
│   │
│   ├── Metrics
│   │   → Measure system performance (CPU, latency, requests/sec).
│   │
│   └── Alerting
│       → Notify teams when issues or thresholds are triggered.
│
└── 10. Deployment
├── Cloud Deployment
│   → Deploy applications on cloud platforms (AWS, Azure, GCP).
│
├── CI/CD
│   → Automated build, test, and deployment pipelines.
│
├── Containerization
│   → Package applications with dependencies using containers.
│
└── Infrastructure as Code
→ Manage infrastructure using code (Terraform, CloudFormation).
